<h2>Overview (TL;DR)</h2>

<p>AMAZE was a disease management platform built to help patients with chronic conditions track their health daily and keep their care teams informed. The core mechanic was a daily health log: a short questionnaire that, when completed, gave clinicians a continuous view of how patients were doing. A pilot study with Massachusetts General Hospital showed completion rates falling steadily over six months. The problem wasn't the product concept. It was that patients had no reason to keep showing up. I joined the team to help scale the platform to new disease states and, alongside that work, helped redesign the log experience to address the drop-off.</p>

<h2>Problem</h2>

<p>The daily health log was the product's most important feature and its most fragile one. Patients with chronic conditions like heart failure or asthma answered between 5 and 15 questions each day about how they were feeling. Their responses went to their care team. If something looked off, the team was alerted. The whole model depended on patients completing it consistently.</p>

<p>A pilot study run with Massachusetts General Hospital showed what was actually happening. Of 30 enrolled participants, 16 completed their log daily in weeks 1 to 4. By weeks 21 to 24, that number had dropped to 7. More than half the engaged patients had stopped. UX research pointed to motivation: patients didn't understand why it mattered, and the repetitive format gave them no reason to keep going.</p>

<p>The design hadn't caused this, but it wasn't helping. The existing experience walked patients through questions one at a time, in a fixed order, every day. It was consistent, but it was also relentless. There was no sense of progress, no flexibility, no way in other than the beginning.</p>

<p>This was also the moment the team was preparing to expand from two diseases to four. Without a shared design system, even adding a new condition risked making an already inconsistent product harder to use.</p>

<blockquote class="pull-quote" role="note">
  <p>"You can't design for trust by making things look trustworthy. You design for trust by removing every moment where the system makes patients feel stupid or scared."</p>
</blockquote>

<h2>Process</h2>

<p>My role split across two parallel workstreams. The first was building a design system for iOS and Android. The second was the health log redesign.</p>

<p>On the design system: when I joined, the asthma and heart failure versions of the app had been built without one. They looked different in ways that were already noticeable, and the team knew that adding more disease states would make it worse. My visual designer and I made an early call to build two separate systems rather than one unified system across platforms. The reasoning was that platform conventions matter in a health context more than in most product categories. Patients managing chronic conditions are often older, less technically confident, and more reliant on familiar interface patterns. Deviating from what iOS or Android users expected felt like the wrong tradeoff.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <p class="callout__label">Research finding</p>
  <p>The most common failure point wasn't a confusing UI — it was jargon. Lab results were displayed with clinical terminology and reference ranges that meant nothing to non-clinicians. Patients didn't know if their numbers were good or bad, and the portal gave them no way to find out without calling the office.</p>
</div>

<p>I built the systems quickly. Over roughly two months, I produced more than 100 components across both platforms. There was real pressure from leadership to move fast. COPD and CKD needed to be designed, and the design system was the prerequisite. I don't think speed compromised the quality in ways that caused immediate problems, but it did mean some decisions were made without much deliberation.</p>

<p>On the health log: my senior designer proposed the concept we eventually explored — a non-linear approach where patients could see the different question categories on a single screen and choose where to start. The hypothesis was that the fixed, linear format felt coercive, and that giving patients more control might sustain motivation. I was responsible for translating that concept into low-fidelity mockups and building the prototypes for research.</p>

<p>Our UX researchers tested two approaches on UserTesting with proxy participants rather than real patients. The first was the existing linear format. The second was the category-selection model. Neither was a clear winner. The linear format was familiar but felt like a grind. The non-linear format gave people agency but introduced confusion about where they were and whether they'd completed everything.</p>

<p>The solution we landed on tried to take what worked from both. From the home screen, patients could tap a single entry point — a "how are you feeling today?" prompt with three response options — and be taken directly into the question flow. Or they could open the full log, select a specific category, answer that question, and be shown the next question rather than returned to the selection screen. The goal was to lower the barrier to starting without losing the structure that made the log clinically useful.</p>

<h2>Solution</h2>

<p>The shipped experience gave patients two ways in: a low-friction entry point from the home screen for those who wanted to complete the log in one go, and a category-first approach for those who preferred to start somewhere specific. Once you answered a question, the app moved you forward rather than dropping you back to a menu. The flow preserved sequence without enforcing it.</p>

