<p>We didn't have completion rate data post-launch. The redesign tested well in UserTesting, and proxy participants found the new entry points less intimidating than the original format. Whether that translated to sustained daily completion is something I can't confirm.</p>

<p>The design system shipped ahead of the COPD and CKD expansions. Both disease states were added quickly. The team was preparing to expand to diabetes when I left.</p>

<h2>Reflection</h2>

<p>The two-system decision for iOS and Android made sense at the time and I still think the reasoning was sound. But maintaining two separate systems when you wanted to change something took twice the work. I'd think harder about that tradeoff now — not because platform conventions don't matter, but because the maintenance cost compounds faster than you expect.</p>

<p>The thing I'd most want to revisit is the research. We tested with proxy participants on UserTesting rather than real patients. For most products that's a reasonable compromise. For a health management app where the users are managing chronic conditions, it's a meaningful gap. The people most likely to disengage from a daily log aren't well-represented by proxy panels. We were testing comprehension and usability. We weren't really testing motivation, which was the actual problem.</p>
